segments.text: Today is April 28th.
I will be interviewing Dr. Alfred D. Fowler.
The location for this interview is in my office in the University Archives.
Again, today's date is Tuesday, April 28th, 1981.
One of the things I ran across in the interview, I was curious about, and it's not particularly important,
Where did you first hear about the job at TFS?
Was it advertised?
At that time, I was working for the International Paper Company.
There was some sort of a ceremony that took place at the Spring Hill Mill of the company.
I can't remember now what it was.
But...
I attended.
Maybe I just decided I wanted to go, or maybe I had gotten an invitation.
I don't remember that.
But at any rate, I ran across two foresters there from Texas.
One was Balzer Koontz, who I had gotten acquainted with many, many years before in Florida.
In the early 30s.
He had lost a job during the Depression with Long Bell, who employed him originally in Texas and Louisiana.
You've heard of the Long Bell Company?
Okay.
And Don Young, they...
had known each other because Kuntz, when he left Florida, he married a Texas girl.
He's a native of Indiana.
Started at Purdue in forestry, then transferred to Syracuse, and then from Syracuse he got this job with Long Bell.
And he had married a Texan, gotten acquainted with her in Jasper.
Although her home had been in Fort Stockton way out west.
At any rate, not a tree for miles.
She had, well, when he was out of a job, I think that they voluntarily came back to Texas.
He made a connection with the Texas Forest Service and then from the Texas Forest Service
He went into the pupwood business.
Well, he at that time was shipping wood to International Paper, the Spring Hill Mill.
That's why he was there.
And whether he and Young traveled over there again, I don't know.
But anyway, I ran across these two fellows.
And like all of us do, we jobbed home for a while.
And Kuhn facetiously, I think, said to me,
Well, I guess you know that there's a vacancy over here in Texas for the directorship of the Texas Forest Service.
And Don Young chimed in, somewhat the same effect.
At the moment, it didn't leave much of an impression with me because I was reasonably happy in the job that I had.
And...

A little while later, I thought it over after I left there, and I thought, well, maybe I'll put in an application for the job over there, largely because I recognized that my opportunity for any advancement in the International Paper Company was quite limited for two reasons.
One, I hadn't been with the company very long.

I was employed by the company in 19, end of 1945, after I came out of military service, largely because of the influence of Earl Porter, who was at that time in charge of procurement for the company in this southern region, and as one who was in charge of procurement, that is, of wood.
He also had charge of land.
But there was somebody immediately below him who administered land, a fellow by the name of Fogelberg, whom I had run across many years before in Florida.
Well, at any rate, Earl Porter hired me.
I had hired him during the CCC days while I was director of the CCC camps in Florida.
He was out of a job or...
was on the verge of being eased out during that deep depression.
He was employed by the Foley Lumber Company at Foley, Florida.
At any rate, Earl hired me, and then as time evolved,
In the early, for the first two years, the 47th and 48th, things went swimmingly for me in Winfield, where I was located in charge of IP lands west of Mississippi.
But then younger men were also released from the military service, fellows who previously had been employed by IP.
Well, I soon recognized that those younger men
were going to be given better opportunities for advancement than I because of those two reasons that I mentioned, my age and not having had any previous experience with IP.
I don't think times have changed too much now.
I think you'd find the same thing if you were in that position in 1981 as you would have in 1947.
Probably so.
Probably so.
It's natural, I guess.
I suppose.
But anyway, I'm not going to elaborate on that.
Anyway, it's water.
Yeah.
So I had gotten acquainted, these fellows had told me that the man who would probably make the decision about the employment of a director was D.W. Williams.
My ears came up like that because I had gotten acquainted with D.W. while we were both in military service.
I got acquainted with him in 1944 in Shrivenham, England.
Run that name by again.
S-H-R-I-V-E-N-H-A-M.
Okay.

And Shrivenham was the place name of what had been the English equivalent or British equivalent of our West Point, but during the war it had no useful purpose anymore and was turned over to U.S. military forces.
Is that where Sandhurst is located?
I don't know, I can't relate to Shrivenham military installation with Sandhurst.
I don't know where Sandhurst is or where it ever was.
But at any rate, Shrivenham was a military installation.
And I was told that it was the equivalent of our West Point, but I had no reason to pursue it.
That's where we people who were in military government were
being, I guess you could say, put in storage until there was a use for us.
Until the Channel Crossing?
Yeah.
Do you remember the exact title of this command that you were in?
Was it just military government or did it have some officious title?
Well, let's see, the title I guess would
At the moment, I can't remember.
Okay, well, it may have just been that.
But we had a designation of G5 in the entire military structure.
Okay, I bet I can find out.
I'm not sure how important it is.
I am curious to know about what you learned from your military experience.
Did it help you in administration?
Did you learn?
No.
You didn't feel like the military was beneficial to your own personal knowledge in any way?
Could be.
Might have been.
I won't go into that, but I had a screwy experience in my military contacts with the military.
Was D.W. over you?
No, no.
He was just there.
He was just there.
He had the rank of major, and I had the rank of captain.
But we all had commissions.
They were made up of entirely commissioned personnel.
Those people are true.
You never met Henry Kissinger, did you?
Oh, Lord, no.
He was in that.
Yeah, but that was after the crossing and in connection with displaced personnel.
I was never identified with that in any way.
Did you stay with military government your entire time in the Army?
No, thank God.
It was the most screwed up outfit I've ever had my misfortune of
Being a part of it.
Then where to after military government?
Well, I wangled a transfer to the Corps of Engineers.
Ah, something you knew something about.
In the Third Army, too.
Pattons.
Yeah.
Were you all just attached to the Corps of Engineers?
No, no.
Do you really want me to go into these things?
I'm just curious.
I'm not going to write about it, but I'm curious.
All right, I'll satisfy your curiosity because I like to talk about this.
While we were driven and we were essentially killing time
So we would wangle or there would be organized trips.
And I was on a trip to Oxford.
And I had remembered back from my days at Yale that Oxford had a course in tropical forestry.
And on the faculty there was a man by the name of, what the hell,
I don't remember at the moment what it was.
So when we got to Oxford, I made it a point to find out where this School of Tropical Forestry was situated on the campus, and I went around there, and I learned that this man...
I wish I could remember.
It'll come back to me tomorrow.
That's not important.
He was in military service.
He had the rank of brigadier.
And he was in military service, and as a matter of fact, he was looking for some foresters.
So this person I talked to at Oxford said, well, I carried this story around with me for a while, several weeks, and then I ran across a fellow also at Shrivenham,
whose name I can't remember at the moment, this is my old age catching up with me, who had a greater rank than I.
He had the rank of major then.
Well, he picked up his ears, and through a whole series of odd circumstances, there was a unit within the engineer section at the Towsa level,
ETOWSA stands for European Theater of U.S.
Forces.

There was a unit within that engineer section of ETOWSA created that would be composed entirely of graduate foresters for the purpose of being deployed among our personnel, U.S. personnel, so that we wouldn't raise hell with the European foresters
like had occurred in World War I.
With the 10th and 20th Engineers.
And this brigadier had been involved in this whole thing in World War I, this English brigadier.
And he was responsible, as I said, for trying to have some foresters set up as a unit within the U.S. forces to do exactly what I mentioned.
And then we in this unit were splattered out among the armies
on the continent, and I was assigned to Third Army.
Oh, I wish I could remember that fellow's name who commanded the unit.
Well, it's not important what his name was.
But at any rate, he said, while we were with the military government, we all wore the unassigned insignia.
You know what that is?
He used to refer to it as a birdcage.
But anyway, when Stan was his first name, maybe I'll think of his name before.
Stan said, now let's get rid of these damn birdcages.
Let's start to wear the engineer corps symbol.
Okay, who was there to say that we couldn't?
All of us trotted out to a supply store and...
got Corps of Engineers insignia, which we probably started to wear after that.
Fortunately, nobody challenged it.
Well, eventually, because of the screwed-up situation, I managed to officially get transferred to the Third Army Corps of Engineers supply officer.
And that's where I was.
And in the meanwhile, while I was still attached to Itaza, I had authority to cross Army lines if I needed to.
And our mission after I got to, was to keep the Paris office informed.
That was where Itaza was situated at the time.
On what the timber supply situation was in each of the armies and what was being done about it.
Well, I could elaborate on that, but at any rate... That sounds like a horrendous job.
Oh, it's... You could goof off 100% of the time if you wanted to, you know.
In other words, you could just guess at what it was.
I certainly could.
But I had a Jeep and a driver at my disposal.
And I had the sort of travel orders where I could stop any place I wanted to.
You weren't involved.
When the Third Army moved across Europe, they moved rather fast.
You weren't having to keep up with them?
No, I was not with Third Army at that time.
Oh, okay.
I was just curious if you were attached to Third Army, if you were forced to constantly move the way they moved.
No, no, no.
This arrangement didn't take place until things had started to stabilize somewhat, that Third Army wasn't moving like it had.
I remember, for example, I was with...
I wasn't assigned to Third Army, but I was with Third Army at the time of the German breakthrough through the Ardennes.
And I got word from the Paris office, Army headquarters, I don't mean Army, I mean ETASA headquarters, to come back to Paris and tell them what the score was.
Hell, this was just, I had a little curiosity on,
on the part of the fellow that headed up our particular unit.
Where were you when the Ardennes breakout started?
Do you remember?
I'm trying to remember.
I was in France somewhere.
I don't exactly remember.
I think it was in the area just west of Metz.
Okay.
Did you ever run across the 26th Division?
Any of those people?
I'm just curious.
My father was in the 26th Division with the Third Army.
When the war ended, he was in Czechoslovakia.
Oh, is that so?
Yeah.
Well, let's get back up to the Forest Service.
There's a question I want to ask you about.
Well, at any rate, I got back home, and I thought about it.
I wrote to DW.
I said, I heard that you have a vacancy in the position of the director of Texas Forest Service.
I got a response from him.
We arranged for interviews, and the sum and substance of it was that he and Chancellor Gale Christ and I met in Lufkin.
This must have been in November, December 1948.
And a kid wanted to get acquainted with me, I guess.
And the upshot of it was I was offered the job, and I accepted, and I reported here January 1, 1949.
Question.
In some of these old papers that I found, it says during your interviews that you were also interviewed by a board from the Texas Forestry Association.
I have no recollection.
You don't remember meeting with any of those people?
No.
Because they were rather favorably impressed with you, according to this.
Either that or Gilchrist is making it up as he goes along.
I have no recollection of meeting anybody from the Texas Forestry Association.
It may have happened.
You may not have known who they were.
Yeah, they may not have identified themselves, but a few years ago, a fellow by the name of Eck... Well, he was at that time a member of the board of the Texas Forestry Association.
He's older than I am.
Made the remark to me that he and he mentioned the other two men
Went to Austin to recommend to the governor that I be designated as the director of the Texas Forest Service.
I want to stop, just a moment.
I don't .
He's the one that told me about that.
Gib Gilchrist wrote to .
a guy by the name of Ruth, it's Peoples.
Yeah.
Who was on the board.
Who was on the board, yeah.
And it said, this morning we talked with a committee from the Texas Forestry Association, and they believe that Fowler's experience is just what we will need.
And Gibb put out some letters to the members of the board, wrote glowing letters.
Which board?
The board of?
Our board.
Oh, the board of directors of A&M.
Okay.
And so the only thing I was curious about when all this was going on was that...
Did you get any idea of what A&M was looking for when they hired you?
Somewhere in here I read they had about 40 applicants.
Forty?
Yeah, that were sent.
I've got a few letters saying, yeah, we'll file them with the rest.
But there's something about you that's different.
I don't think any other PhDs applied.
No, because PhDs in the ministry were as scarce as hen's teeth at that time.
did you get any impression from Gilchrist that this was a way to upgrade?
They would be concerned with it now.
I doubt if they would have.
Well, I don't know that they would have then, but I was thinking if maybe Gilchrist is saying, here's a man with broad experience.
He's got state experience.
He's got private industry.
He's got some federal work.
He has the academic credentials.
Well, I was also on the faculty for almost 10 years at LSU.
Yeah, so he's got the academic credentials.
Here's a man that is both industry and both academic.
And they wouldn't have had anything.
Now, people within the Forest Service applied for this job.
And I got letters in here from Don Young and Ann .
All these people had applied.
But from looking over it, then there was no question.
On paper, you had to be the best credential-wise.
And I was just wondering if Forest Service, where they said, he's the best man.
We want to upgrade the directorship of the program from what it was.
We're going to get a high-powered individual in here.
I just wondered if there was any feeling that you got that they were going to upgrade.
Well, I was told by Kuntz over there at that meeting at Spring Hill when we were attending that I've heard they're willing to pay as much as $10,000 if they get the right man.
Why?
Oh, I don't know.
I'm curious about that.
Why suddenly do they care?
I don't know.
I don't see any evidence of caring in the past.
No, you're so right.
You're so right.
Which reminds me that soon after I came here, I was somewhat conscious of public relations, and I arranged to set up an advisory committee of nine people to be appointed for two-year periods.
eventually getting into an overlapping situation like they have on the board of directors here in the regions.
Gibb wouldn't hear of two years.
One year was all right.
So he attended the first meeting.
One of the men that I had persuaded to be a member represented the champion paper, and he was a pretty blunt sort of fellow.
He said to Gib Gilchrist, why does the Texas Forest Service always have to suck in the hind tit of this A&M cow?
And it was certainly true that they had done that.
Do you remember who that was that said that?
Oh, the name of Crow.
Crow.
C-R-O-W-R-O-W.
I don't have an old list of that thing.
I've got some of the later ones in the 50s, and I don't have his...
I imagine if I look real hard, I can find it.
What gave you the idea for setting up the advisory committee?

Well, there, somehow I think I had picked up the idea that there wasn't any communication really between the industry that was a principal, had the principal interest in the Texas Forest Service because of controlled fire, and the organization.
So I thought, well, there are less, more landowners
interested in this, too, I would suppose.
And I thought, well, this will be a means whereby they'll be willing to tell me, because there are several of them, what they think, what ways in which the Texas Forest Service could be improved.
Was this a conscious public relations effort on your part, in a way?
Yeah, yeah.
It would work both ways.
Here you are stuck in College Station.
Not stuck, but the headquarters is here.
And it's a way to get them over here and to talk about things?
Or did you go to them?
No.
We had these meetings here in College Station in the director's office.
So it was nice to get industry in one location, at least leaders of industry, rather than you making a circuit around.
I suppose I could have gotten this same
thing from the Texas Forestry Association.
But the Texas Forestry Association at that time was something of a non-entity.
And I didn't think well of it because while I was in Louisiana, another fellow and I were instrumental in creating the Louisiana Forestry Association.
I'm surprised they didn't have one before then.
Well, they had sort of a half-assed organization over there.
It was led by a man by the name of Hartner from Urania, and he was something of a leader in forestry.
He was one of the very, very few sawmillers who was trying to practice some semblance of forestry.
Yes.
In fact, he was, Goodrich Jones used to refer to him as the first, and got into a big argument with Lynch Davidson over Lynch Davidson claiming he had been over every inch of Urania land, and
Goodrich wrote to Hartner.
Hartner said, I've never seen a man on my land before he's lying.
Okay.
So one quick question about Louisiana.
You ever heard of a man by the name of Forbes?
R.D.
Forbes.
What did R.D.
stand for, do you know?
Reginald.
Damn, I remember what his middle name is.
That's good enough.
Reginald Denny Forbes, I think.
Reginald?
R.D.
Forbes.
He was director of the Southern Forest Experiment Station.
Okay, because he at one time was, of course, a state forester in Louisiana in the early years.
One of their first.
Very short time.
And then he went on someplace else.
But he was over in Texas helping out with Texas Forestry Association at one time.
Oh, is that so?
Oh, he came over to speak.
They traded people back and forth, that sort of thing.
When you...
first took over the Texas Forest Service, what did you find?
A demoralized organization.
Why demoralized?
Well, I don't think that White ever exerted much leadership.
He succeeded Siki as state forester.
And then Frost was acting.
He was acting, and then Anderson was acting, and...
Frankly, I don't know why Frost wasn't selected.
But I think maybe some of the people in the industry felt that nobody from within the organization should be selected as director, because that would cause too much cleavage.
Don Young had Kurth's backing initially, or at least the company had.
Ernest Kurth?
Well, through one of his minions.
OK.
Through the lumber company initially.
Well, Don, you see, would have contact with, because his job in the Texas Forest Service was contacting industry.
Yes, yes.
So you found it demoralized, you feel, because of lack of leadership on White's part.
Curious thing that I don't know is that during World War II, I don't know what the problems were in the industry or within the Forest Service, there was
Pretty good expansion during World War II as far as buying equipment that they never had.
They didn't have a mechanized tractor until 1941.
They got them two-wheel tractors.
They got five of them.
And then they'd be able to, with those federal emergency funds, they purchased equipment and I guess got to keep it.
Oh, yeah.
And there was expansion.
I'm sure there were some personnel problems.
I'm sure there was a shortage of manpower during the war.
Yes.
But I didn't see anything within that part I looked at.
It looked like nice growth, a few new programs, the war ends, and then it turned sour on him.
Something had to have happened to White.
I don't know what it was, whether this lack of leadership finally got him in a whole lot of trouble, that the thing fell apart on him.
Well, one handicap that Bill had was that his wife would never come over here to live.
He married...
woman in Lufkin.
You see, he was chief of the fire control section.
His responsibility was fire.
Had been since 1930.
Well, I don't know how far back that went.
Well, at any rate, then when he was selected for a job that was vacated by Siki, she wouldn't come over here and live with him.
She'd visit occasionally.
Bill was operating under something of a handicap, I'd say.
Maybe that affected his general attitude toward the job.
I have a sneaking suspicion he somehow got crossways with Gilchrist.
Not, I still...
We didn't have much time to because the system organization wasn't created until just about a year, year and a half before I came here.
Gilchrist had been president and he'd been reporting to Gilchrist.
Oh, I don't know.
I guess so.
I have a feeling that something happened in there.
I think the event that caused the thing that everybody talks about is just a tip.
Could be.
This was like an excuse to get rid of somebody.
Could be.
Maybe Anderson has something on it.
He'll have an opinion, I'm sure.
But it just seemed to me that something went wrong between 1945 and 1948.
Could be.
Something really went wrong.
So you found a demoralized agency.
And the finances were in a shambles.
Why?
What damn if I know?
They just weren't, huh?
They were in a shambles because Bill White didn't concern himself any.
There was no financial control at all?
Hardly any.
That was one of the first things I did.
Can you tell me anything about financial control, just in a nutshell?
I'm not sure I understand your question.
About what it is that you did to establish financial control.
Oh, well, first of all, I created a budget.
He never had a budget before?
Not that I know of.
Oh, there was a semblance of one.
He had to have something to present to the U.S. Forest Service.
Yeah, the Clark McNary reports had something of it, but it was more of an after-the-fact.
Yeah.
And the state budget was broken down broadly.
Very broadly.
What kind of a budget did you prepare?
Was it a, what are the terms they use now?
I'm not an accountant.
There are several types of budgets.
Well, I created an overall budget for the agency, broken down by departments and by districts.
Also, I created an organization in the field which really hadn't existed.
What's that?
Well, I created six districts, administrative districts.
Up until that time, there had been no real field activity other than fire control, and fire control operated out of Joe Burnside's desk over in Lufkin.
Just out of his desk?
Yeah.
Now, the six districts then, did they not have anything, if this straightens my mind, they weren't then necessarily controlled with fire control?
No.
That was a major function.
So the only organization really in East Texas up until you came was the fire control organization.
Right.
A highly decentralized organization.
Did you not reduce the number of divisions also?
Weren't there five when you came and you reorganized it down to four?
Four.
Do you recall why?
Or just made it streamlined or more efficient?
I don't know why.
I wasn't conscious of the fact that there were five.
Well, I set it up.
I guess, yes.
Well, I would have to scratch my head more than I can right now.
But I don't remember what the five might have been, but we had four.
One was forest products, fire control, management, and I&E.
They don't break it down in some of these older reports as to what they were.
They would say, forest management, industrial forestry.
Well, excuse me, that industrial forestry was contained in one person, Coons, at this point.
Well, later on by Don Young.
Yeah.
Civil cultural research, forest products research, and then they had it broken down by the nursery.
Then they just called it information.
Well, I'll tell you, the fifth one was research.
Okay.
I eliminated that.
And put it under what?
Well, I eliminated research as a function.
You didn't do any more research at that point?
No.
No, my position was that with a very, very limited budget that we had, we had no damn business doing research.
Well, good question, because what I did was, in looking through the war years,

They didn't do a whole lot of research until World War II, and then they just kind of played with it, and it looked to me as if they were redoing research that was being done by the federal people already.
Oh, they were messing around with it.
Dave Anderson was messing around with it.
Okay.
They were making plastics out of pecan holes.
Well, now that was done over at the Forest Products Laboratory.
Yeah.
Now, you didn't close that, did you?
No, no.
But you moved them under someone else?
No, that was a...
Separate situation now.
No.
Essentially, what the Forest Products...
Department, and it's called LAB now.
Well, essentially what they did over there was conducted investigative projects.
Well, I guess you could, if you use the word research very broadly, you could say, yes, they did forest products research.
I see.
Okay.
Well, you can see the limitations in my understanding, and looking at it from the outside, I get this back and forth.
Okay, well, what you did, in effect, was really just kind of streamline the whole thing, get rid of unnecessary elements.
You felt research was... Well, there was a lack of cohesion in the whole effort.
Who was doing the... Now, this research, where was it being carried on?
Here?
No.
No, which research?
Well, you were talking about...
There are two types of research.
The one that you're getting...
I'd like to know about the one that you wanted to get rid of.
Civil cultural research.
Civil cultural research.
That was... Dave Anderson headed that up here, and he had...
a subordinate over at Kirbyville by the name of Ted Silker.
Okay.
Ted did all the work and Andy did the supervising.
From here?
Yeah.
It's kind of long distance.
Oh, sure.
Okay.
And White condoned all of this long distance kind of operation?
Oh, sure.
Or did he just not care?
I don't think he cared.
He wasn't interested in research.
Well, he didn't have enough budget to be
Not having any.
He didn't have enough budget to have fat in it.
In such a tiny little budget.
I don't know what it was.
Well, it wasn't much.
It was damn small, I know, when I came here.
It's not real large now compared to other things.
Well, it's amazingly large considering what the job is.
Okay.
So, in a way, now you've made the Forest Service more efficient.
Now, demoralized problems,
That's a morale problem within the, what'd you do about that?
Or could you do it?
Well, there wasn't much I could do about it.
Yeah.
But, see, here was Joe Burnside.
He wanted to be director, too.
I don't know how hard he tried, but he would have liked to have been director.
I think everybody would have.
As a matter of fact, this is kind of small of me to mention, but I will anyway.
Not long after I got here,
and I was trying to organize a budget.
I was talking to Joe Burnside over there in his office, and he showed me a budget that he had prepared for the Texas Forest Service, and he had shown how much my salary should be.
That illustrates the lack of finesse that Joe had.
Joe, in some respects, was...
He was a pretty good organizer.
He was overburdened, though, with formalities and forms.
He was over-organized considering what he had to work with.
He was pretty much desk-bound, too.
But morale was really not much you could do other than See, I inherited these fellows.
Oh, yeah.
Now, anybody that comes in is going to inherit a lot of problems.
Did you get rid of any people?
No, I didn't.
Finally, I made things uncomfortable enough where Gene, a fellow over at the Forest Products Department, had left him.
So he left.
So you only had a minor shakeup in personnel over a period of time.
Yeah.
Did you bring in any of your own people?
No, I had nobody to bring in.
There was nobody that you...
Many times administrators coming in want to bring in some of their people.
No, in my case, there wasn't anybody I wanted to bring in with me.
Okay.
Well, then you decided to up your PR standards by creating the advisory committee.
Of course, this may have been a help also to morale.
If industry took an interest in you, maybe that would have been expressed back through the field, and if your people felt like industry was interested, that might have helped.
It might have a double effect.
It might have.
I'm not sure, though, about that.
One, the people that were in before you left, both Anderson and Frost... Before I left?
I mean, before you came, I get the impression they were just caretakers.
Essentially, yeah.
They couldn't make any real decisions.
Once I asked D.W. Williams, well, I guess I should have been a little more subtle than I was, but...
I'm the sort of fellow that's not as subtle as I should be.
I'm a little blunt.
I said to DW, why didn't you people make Anderson director?
DW, he's a pretty subtle sort of fellow.
I said, oh, we didn't think he was quite ready for it.
And that was the end of that.
